    <h2 id="what-is-coq10">What Is CoQ10 and Why Your Body Needs It</h2>

    <p>Coenzyme Q10 — also known as ubiquinone or ubiquinol depending on its oxidation state — is a vitamin-like compound found in every cell of your body. It serves two critical biological functions: first, it is an essential cofactor in the mitochondrial electron transport chain, the metabolic pathway that produces approximately 95% of your body's cellular energy (ATP); second, it is one of the most powerful fat-soluble antioxidants in human biology, protecting cell membranes, mitochondrial DNA, and LDL cholesterol particles from oxidative damage.</p>

    <p>The organs with the highest energy demands — the heart, liver, kidneys, and skeletal muscles — contain the greatest concentrations of CoQ10. The heart alone requires so much CoQ10 that cardiac tissue contains 10 times the concentration found in other tissues. When CoQ10 levels decline, these high-demand organs are the first to suffer, manifesting as fatigue, reduced exercise tolerance, and compromised cardiovascular function. If you are looking for other supplements to support overall wellness, explore our <a href="/vitamins/">vitamins and health gummies</a> category for comprehensive options.</p>

