      <p class="key-stat-txt">decline in natural CoQ10 production by age 50. Your body's CoQ10 synthesis peaks around age 20 and decreases steadily thereafter. By age 40, cardiac CoQ10 levels have dropped by <strong>32%</strong>, and by age 80, heart tissue CoQ10 is <strong>57% below</strong> the level found in 20-year-olds. Statin medications compound this decline by blocking the same enzymatic pathway that produces both cholesterol and CoQ10.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The gummy format is particularly well-suited for CoQ10 supplementation because CoQ10 is notoriously difficult to absorb. As a fat-soluble compound with large molecular weight, standard CoQ10 powders in capsules have bioavailability as low as 2-3%. Gummies inherently contain fats from their gelatin or pectin base and added oils, providing the lipid matrix that CoQ10 requires for intestinal absorption. This built-in delivery advantage makes <strong>CoQ10 gummies</strong> a practical choice for consistent, absorbable supplementation — especially for individuals who already take multiple capsules daily and want to reduce pill burden.</p>

